I deeply appreciate the work the WPILib contributors have done on the 2027 updates, but I’m not a fan of the new coroutine system. The forced use of `coroutine.yield()` in every loop feels unnecessary and risky—missing it could cause my robot to explode without any warnings. Additionally, explaining `coroutine.fork()` and `coroutine.yield()` becomes challenging for junior programmers, as it requires extensive lectures on signals and threading. While the V2 Commands library simplifies understanding command handling, teaching these concepts takes only five minutes, and composing commands there is both elegant and clean. For instance, writing a scoring command looks straightforward:

```java
public Command score(ReefLevel level) {
    return elevator.moveToAndHold(level)
        .until(elevator::atTargetHeight)
        .deadlineFor(coral.stow())
        .andThen(coral.scoreAtLevel(level))
        .withName("Score " + level.name());
}
```

This approach reads naturally, unlike the new API’s reliance on native loops. If the new API’s main benefit is enabling native control structures within commands, it may not justify its cost.

What’s even worse is that <strong>if I somehow forget to add this single line, MY ROBOT WILL EXPLODE</strong>. And I get absolutely zero warning or error about it during compile or deploy.

Yep. That’s the glaring footgun with the coroutine-first approach; there’s no way to check at compile time so it’s up to the programmer to be aware of it. A watchdog will be necessary to detect misbehaving commands and throw an exception if one is taking too much time before yielding (continuations aren’t threadsafe, so I don’t think it’s possible to do something like forcibly unmounting a running command from a different thread, though future Java updates might change that).

Maybe it’s useful if you consider <code>coroutine.yield()</code> to be analogous to <code>Thread.sleep(20)</code>.

The scoring command that you’ve mentioned can be written as:

public Command score(ReefLevel level) {
  return elevator.moveToAndHold(level)
      .until(elevator::atTargetHeight)
      .deadlineFor(coral.stow())
      .andThen(coral.scoreAtLevel(level))
      .withName("Score " + level.name());
}

Not quite - the elevator is uncommanded during the coral scoring command at the end. If you use onboard motor control, then the elevator could sag (you’d have to use something like <code>coral.scoreAtLevel(level).deadlineFor(elevator.holdLastKnownSetpoint())</code>, which isn’t obvious).

Such code just looks so beautiful and reads like natural language.

That’s if you’re used to the DSL - but I generally agree that it’s better to express intent in your code than implementation (ie, declarative programming > imperative programming). The issue with DSLs, though, is that there’s a learning curve to the syntax and framework behavior, and that’s not always easy.

There will still be DSL-like decorators and builders in v3 like <code>until</code>, <code>withTimeout</code>, <code>alongWith</code>, etc, and - because they’re a higher-level part of the framework - don’t particularly care about how commands are implemented at a lower level.

It’s pretty easy to add a v2-like shim layer if you really want (see below); though I’m not yet convinced that we’d want something like this included in the library. Convenience factories for simple looping commands (eg <code>Command.loop(Runnable)</code> I think would be good fits, but if you’re doing something more complicated - that’s where coroutines are more powerful.

CommandBuilder v2Shim(
    Runnable init,
    Runnable execute,
    BooleanSupplier isFinished,
    BooleanConsumer onExit) {

  return run(coroutine -> {
    init.run();

    while (!isFinished.getAsBoolean()) {
      execute.run();
      coroutine.yield();
    }

    onExit.accept(false);
  }).whenCanceled(() -> onExit.accept(true));
}

Here’s a homing command shared by @bankst in an unofficial Discord server last week:

V2
```java
public Command currentSenseHoming() {
    Runnable init = () -> {
        System.out.println("Elevator Zero INIT");
        m_frontMotor.getConfigurator().apply(kSoftLimitSwitchDisabledConfig);
        m_frontMotor.setControl(m_voltageCtrlReq.withOutput(-1));
    };
    Runnable execute = () -> {};
    Consumer<Boolean> onEnd = (Boolean interrupted) -> {
        if (interrupted) {
            System.out.println("Elevator homing INTERRUPTED!");
            return;
        }
        m_frontMotor.setPosition(0);
        m_frontMotor.setControl(m_voltageCtrlReq.withOutput(0));
        removeDefaultCommand();
        m_isHomed = true;
        m_frontMotor.getConfigurator().apply(kSoftwareLimitConfigs);
        System.out.println("Zeroed Elevator!!!");
    };

    return new FunctionalCommand(init, execute, onEnd, notMoving(m_homingCurrSpike), this);
}

V3  
```  
```java
public Command currentSenseHoming() {
  return run(coroutine -> {
    System.out.println("Elevator Zero INIT");
    m_frontMotor.getConfigurator().apply(kSoftLimitSwitchDisabledConfig);
    m_frontMotor.setControl(m_voltageCtrlReq.withOutput(-1));

    var detection = notMoving(m_homingCurrSpike);
    while (!detection.getAsBoolean()) {
      coroutine.yield();
    }

    m_frontMotor.setPosition(0);
    m_frontMotor.setControl(m_voltageCtrlReq.withOutput(0));
    removeDefaultCommand();
    m_isHomed = true;
    m_frontMotor.getConfigurator().apply(kSoftwareLimitConfigs);
    System.out.println("Zeroed Elevator!!!");
  })
  .whenCancelled(() -> System.out.println("Elevator homing INTERRUPTED!"))
  .named("Elevator Homing");
}
